The impacts of the solution pH and incubation duration were assessed and improved to obtain the best measurement activityfor Fe3+ sensing. Selectivity experiments with various metal ions were conducted to estimate the sensing performance of the NSB-CDs. The UV–Vis absorption and PL intensities were examined by adding various metal ions (Ag+, Ce3+, Ca2+, Hg2+, Cu2+, Sn2+, Ni2+, Ti3+, Mn2+, Zn2+, Ba2+, Pb2+, Cd2+, Co2+, Sr2+, Na+, and Fe3+) at 25 µM concentration to NSB-CD solutions (5 μg/mL). Upon addition of Hg2+, Fe3+, and Pb2+, the intensity of the band at 450 nm diminished, while absorption of the band at 232, 274, and 242 nm was enhanced [47] (Fig. 3
                        a). As shown in Fig. 3b, Fe3+ exhibited the high PL quenching of NSB-CDs, whereas no significant changes in PL were observed for the other metal ions. Accordingly, NSB-CDs turn off PL as Fe3+-specific chemosensors [48]. With the naked eye, the solution of NSB-CDs with Fe3+ changed from bright green to yellow under 365 nm UV lamp irradiation, while the addition of other metal ions at similar concentrations did not result in any color change (Fig. 3c). An aqueous NSB-CD solution was treated with Fe3+ under UV illumination at 365 nm, and the strongly green color of the solution changed to yellow within 8 s (Video 1). The PL spectra of NSB-CDs treated with a PBS solution (pH 7.4) containing various amounts of Fe3+ were obtained at excitation at 450 nm and emission at 455–750 nm (Fig. 4
                        ). Emission intensity at 524 nm gradually decreased with increasing Fe3+ concentrations (0–25 μM) [49]. As illustrated in Fig. 4a, a potent new PL emission peak was established at 541 nm, and PL intensity underwent 16-fold quenching. The change in the emission color of the NSB-CDsolution from dark green to brilliant yellow further confirmed the PL turn-off, with red-shifted emission peaks from 524 to 541 nm of the NSB-CD/Fe3+ solution [50] (Fig. 4a, inset). In Fig. 4b, the P/P0 values were plotted against Fe3+ concentrations to obtain the calibration curve.
